Final Project

Time Series

We will be analysing a time series based on the database of food inspections in the city of chicago.
The data set is in the file “food-inspections.csv”. As it is not originaly a time series, we need to, after loading it, transform the data into a time series.

#libraries required
library(astsa)
library(zoo)
library(ggplot2)
library(forecast)
library(lubridate)
library(readr)
library(tseries)
## Warning: package 'tseries' was built under R version 3.6.2
#load database from file
food_inspections <- read_csv("C:/Users/zé/Desktop/programação/R/STP/Final Work/food-inspections.csv")

#get data on the dates and the results of inspections
inspectionDateTable = food_inspections["Inspection Date"]
resultsTable = food_inspections["Results"]

#preprocessing of data
resultsList = unlist(resultsTable)
inspectionDateList = as.Date(unlist(inspectionDateTable)/(24*60*60))
resultsFilterList = ifelse(resultsList == "Pass",1,ifelse(resultsList == "Fail",1,1))
inspectionMatrix = matrix(c(inspectionDateList,resultsFilterList),nrow = length(inspectionDateList),ncol = 2)
inspectionMatrixFilter = inspectionMatrix[inspectionMatrix[,2]==1,]

#aggregate inspections by month and turn it into a time series
inspectionMatrixByMonth = aggregate(inspectionMatrixFilter[,2],by=list(year(as.Date(inspectionMatrixFilter[,1]))*12+month(as.Date(inspectionMatrixFilter[,1]))),FUN=sum)
inspectionTS = ts(inspectionMatrixByMonth[,2],start = c(2010,1),end = c(2019,9),frequency = 12)

The series is updated every day, as such the last month is not complete and was removed.
There is a know break in the data wich occured in the start of 2018 due to policy change.

The series has the following parameters.
Sampling frequency: monthly
Start date: 01/2010
End date: 09/2019
Length: 116 months

par(mfrow=c(3,1))
tsplot(inspectionTS,main="Monthly Inspections")
acf(inspectionTS)
pacf(inspectionTS)

Transformations and Differencing

We can easly spot the break in the data at the previously mentioned location.
As we are dealing with monthly data we will ajust the data to the number of days
in a month and see if it improves.

monthdays = rep(c(31,28,31,30,31,30,31,31,30,31,30,31),10)
monthdays[26 + (4*12)*(0:1)] = 29
monthdays=monthdays[0:117]
AvgInspectionTS = inspectionTS/monthdays
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
plot(inspectionTS, main="Monthly Inspections",
  ylab="Count",xlab="Years")
plot(AvgInspectionTS, main="Average Inspections per day", 
  ylab="Count", xlab="Years")

We can see that the plot is almost the same, as such the transformtaion was not usefull
and will not be kept.

There are no obvious changes in the variability of the data throughout time. Therefore
we will not be performing a box-cox transformation.

From the ACF we can conclude that the data has a 1 year(12 month) seasonal component. As
such seasonal differencing will be performed.

sDiffInspectionTs = diff(inspectionTS,lag=12)
par(mfrow=c(3,1))
tsplot(sDiffInspectionTs,main="Seasonally Differenced Inspections", 
  ylab="Count", xlab="Years")
acf(sDiffInspectionTs,main="Seasonally Differenced Inspections ACF")
pacf(sDiffInspectionTs,main="Seasonally Differenced Inspections PACF")

At this point seasonality is no longer detected. It is not clear if we need to perform
regular differencing, as such we will use a Kwiatkowski-Phillips-Schmidt-Shin (KPSS) test,
a test for the stationarity of a time series.

kpss.test(sDiffInspectionTs)
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  sDiffInspectionTs
## KPSS Level = 0.65671, Truncation lag parameter = 4, p-value =
## 0.01748

As the p-value is quite small (0.01748) we can reject the null hypotheses, that the data is
stationary. As such we will perform differencing.

diffInspectionTs = diff(sDiffInspectionTs)
par(mfrow=c(3,1))
tsplot(diffInspectionTs,main="Seasonally and First Differenced Inspections")
acf(diffInspectionTs)
pacf(diffInspectionTs)

At this point the series looks stationary, however lets perform a second KPSS test to confirm.

kpss.test(diffInspectionTs)
## Warning in kpss.test(diffInspectionTs): p-value greater than printed p-
## value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  diffInspectionTs
## KPSS Level = 0.031329, Truncation lag parameter = 4, p-value = 0.1

We can see that the p-value is now above the tipical confidence level of 0.05, and as such
we will assume that the data is stationary.

Modeling

Given that we now know the required differencing to make the series stationary, we will perform
modeling.
We will try to obtain to models from distinct families of models.
The first one is an sarima model.
The second one will be an exponential smothing model.

But first we will divide the data into a train and test set.

inspectionsTrain = window(inspectionTS, end=c(2018,9))
inspectionsTest = window(inspectionTS, start=c(2018,10))

Sarima Models

and for the autoregressive component

The ACF has 1 significant value, while the PACF has 2. We also know that there is a seasonal
component of 12 months. First we will try to vary the seasonal part of the model. After
selecting the best seasonal component we will try to find the best arma component.

For seasonality we will try (0,0),(0,1),(0,2),(1,0),(1,1),(1,2),(2,0),(2,1),(2,2), while
seting the arma to (0,0).

The (2,2),(3,0) and (3,2) created an optimization error, and as such have been discarded.

The best model was the Sarima(1,1,1,2,1,1)12, as such now we will show the fitted
model and the ACF and PACF of the residuals.

fitArima = Arima(inspectionsTrain, order=c(1,1,1), seasonal=c(2,1,1))

Exponential Smothing

Exponential smoothing designates a set of methods for forecasting that are
essentially non parametric in the sense that you do not find a model for the
data and iterate the model to obtain forecasts. Also these methods do not require
assumptions such as stationarity, Gaussianity, etc. The forecasts are computed from
the data with weights that decay exponentially.

The predictions are made using a parameter alpha, with higher alpha the more distant
observations gain more weight, while with lower alpha the oposite is true.
Alpha must bettwen 0 and 1 in order to be invertible. For alpha of 0 the predicted value
will allways be 0, while with 1 the output will be the mean of all previous observations.

The basic formula for the predictions is:
y^T+1|T = αyT + α(1 − α)yT−1 + α(1 − α)^2yT−2 + ⋯

A lot of variations exist, including those with seasonal components and trend components
For these 2 more parameters must be selected or estimated, gamma and beta, for seasonal and
trend, respectively.

Exponential Smothing Aplication

We have had no practice in class about how to pick the ES models by hand, as such all models
will be automaticaly selected.

For this work we will use the ets function, wich has both trend and seasonal components.
It also automaticaly selects the best parameters based on the data.

Forecasting

We will show the time series in black and both the fitted model and predictions in blue.
The forecast interval will be the last year.

Hand picked sarima models

autoplot(forecast(fitArima,h=12)) +
  autolayer(inspectionTS, series="Real series",color = "black") + 
  autolayer(fitArima$fitted, series="Fitted series",color = "blue") +
ylab("Number of food inspections per month.")

The obtained forecasts seems perfectly reasonable, with most values inside the 95% band.
However it would seem that due to the variance of the process the predicted(most likely) values
are quite far from the real ones.

Automatically selected Sarima model

autoplot(forecast(fitArimaAuto,h=12)) +
  autolayer(inspectionTS, series="Real series",color = "black") + 
  autolayer(fitArimaAuto$fitted, series="Fitted series",color = "blue") +
ylab("Number of food inspections per month.")

The same can be said about this model as the previous one, however the forecast seems just slightly worse.
The difference is still small enough that further analisys will be performd to pick bettwen the 2.

Automatically selected Esponential smothing model

autoplot(forecast(fitETS,h=12)) +
  autolayer(inspectionTS, series="Real series",color = "black") + 
  autolayer(fitETS$fitted, series="Fitted series",color = "blue") +
ylab("Number of food inspections per month.")

As we can see, the fit seems quite good, however the predictions are poor, with most values not even
laying on the bands of confidence. This may be due to the nature of the problem, as there is the
previously mentioned change in the data.

Since the forecasts are so poor lets show the acf to see if we managed to use all the information.

acf(resid(fitArimaAuto))

The acf doesn’t have any value outside the confidence bands, so it seems we fitted the data correctly.
However just to be sure lets do a box test.

Box.test(resid(fitArimaAuto))
## 
##  Box-Pierce test
## 
## data:  resid(fitArimaAuto)
## X-squared = 0.0010824, df = 1, p-value = 0.9738

The box test gives a high p-value, so we conclude the values are not correlated
and as such we can now conclude that the residuals are white noise.

Hand Picked Esponential smothing model

autoplot(forecast(fitETSHand,h=12)) +
  autolayer(inspectionTS, series="Real series",color = "black") + 
  autolayer(fitETSHand$fitted, series="Fitted series",color = "blue") +
ylab("Number of food inspections per month.")

The prediction obtained by the hand selected exponential smothing model are better than those from the automatically selected model, however, they are still quite poor, with most values not even
laying on the bands of confidence. This may be due to the nature of the problem, as there is the
previously mentioned change in the data.

Since the forecasts are so poor lets show the acf to see if we managed to use all the information.

acf(resid(fitETSHand))

The acf only shows one value outside the confidence bands, so it seems we fitted the data correctly.
However just to be sure lets do a box test.

Box.test(resid(fitETSHand))
## 
##  Box-Pierce test
## 
## data:  resid(fitETSHand)
## X-squared = 0.0037095, df = 1, p-value = 0.9514

The box test gives a high p-value, so we conclude the values are not correlated
and as such we can now conclude that the residuals are white noise.

Given that the data was fitted correctly but the forecasts are poor for both the models
we come to the conclusion that the exponential smothing model is not good for this data.

As we can see the errors in the test set for the hand picked model is smaller that for the one automatically selected.
Therefore the final and best model is the Sarima(1,1,1)(2,1,1)12.

The question of usefullness of the model still persists.The forecasts are quite good and even with the change of the
series in 2018 we manage to capture the change, however the real values stay within the 95% bands but far away from
the predicted values, wich means that we have to take in consideration the entire band.
That is a problem, from 2010 to 2018 the mean remained mostly unchanged, with only variability around it.
The bands are almost as wide as said variability, as such were we to use such large confidence bands in
that section, the predictions would be about as good as using the mean.

Conclusion

We managed to capture the series and obtain good forecasts, however there are some concerns of usability.
If in the future the mean stabilizes, much like on the past, and the variance of the model does not reduce
then the model is not usefull, on the other hand if either of those proves untrue, while the forecasts remain
good, then the model is a usefull one.
